{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}} {{Infobox military conflict |conflict=Battle of One Tree Hill |date=12 September 1843 |place=Tabletop Mountain (then known as "One Tree Hill"), [[Darling Downs]], [[Queensland]], [[Australia]]. |result=Jagera victory |combatant1={{flagicon|British Empire}} British colonists |combatant2=[[File:Australian Aboriginal Flag.svg|23px|border]] [[Jagera]] people |commander1=Commissioner Simpson |commander2=Multuggera |strength1= 18 |strength2= over 100 |casualties1= |casualties2= }}
'''The Battle of One Tree Hill''' was the best known of a series of conflicts that took place between European settlers and aboriginal inhabitants of the [[Darling Downs]] in the 1840s.
In September 1843, aboriginal leader Multuggera led an ambush of squatters taking supplies across from [[Moreton Bay]], at One Tree Hill (now known as Tabletop Mountain), near [[Toowoomba]].<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/bigideas/table-top-mountain/4765242 "Table Top Mountain", ''Big Ideas - National''] accessed 23 February 2014</ref>
The squatters organised a revenge party and the aborigines retreated up the mountain. They escaped into the [[Lockyer Valley]] but were later tracked down and killed by the military.<ref>[https://www.nla.gov.au/pub/nlanews/2011/jun11/a-picture-asks-a-thousand-questions.pdf "A Picture Asks a Thousand Questions", ''National Library of Australia'', 11 June 2011] accessed 19 February 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.thechronicle.com.au/news/darling-downs-history-national-library-australia/666255/ Louise O'Keefe, "Darling Downs History on Display", ''The Chronicle'', 23 October 2010] accessed 19 February 2014</ref>
A monument recording the battle was established in 2005.<ref>[http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/133629/20120518-1552/monumentaustralia.org.au/monument_display0f65.php Multuggerah at ''Monument Australia''] accessed 23 Feb 2014</ref> An indigenous land use agreement has been signed over the site.<ref>[http://www.nntt.gov.au/news-and-communications/media-releases/pages/indigenouslanduseagreementsignedintoowoomba.aspx "Indigenous land use agreement signed in Toowoomba" 27 Feb 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140211230619/http://www.nntt.gov.au/news-and-communications/media-releases/pages/indigenouslanduseagreementsignedintoowoomba.aspx |date=February 11, 2014 }} accessed 23 Feb 2014</ref>
In 2010, the [[National Library of Australia]] acquired a sketch by local Thomas John Domville Taylor for $120,000 which is believed to be an eyewitness account of the aftermath of the battle. This made it one of less than ten visual eyewitness accounts of attacks by European settlers on indigenous people.<ref>[http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-national/library-acquires-indigenous-attack-account-20101022-16wh7.html "Library acquires indigenous attack account", ''Sydney Morning Herald'', 22 October 2010] accessed 23 February 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/image-of-frontier-battle-comes-to-life/story-e6frg6nf-1225942452434 Sarah Elks, "Image of frontier battle comes to life", ''The Australian'' 23 October 2010] accessed 23 February 2014</ref>
