{{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = | name = Grace Simpson | honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA}} | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1920|11|12|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Boston Spa]], [[West Yorkshire]] | death_date = {{death date and age |2007|2|8 |1920|11|12 |df=yes}} | death_place = [[Oxford]] | death_cause = | occupation = Archaeologist | awards = | alma_mater = [[Oxford University]] | thesis_title = | discipline = Classical Archaeology | sub_discipline = Roman archaeology, Roman ceramics | workplaces ={{Plainlist| * Durham University * Chesters Roman Fort * Oxford University * Haverford College }} }} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}
'''Mary Grace Simpson''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA}} (12 November 1920 &ndash; 8 February 2007) was a British archaeologist and museum curator specialising in the study of Roman ceramics, especially [[Terra sigillata|Samian ware]].<ref name="ARA">{{cite journal |url=https://www.associationromanarchaeology.org/ARA_Bulletin18_pages16to30.pdf |author1=Bird, J. |date=December 2007 |title=Grace Simpson (1920-2007) |journal=[[Association of Roman Archaeology]] Bulletin |volume=18 |pages=18-20}}</ref>
==Biography== ===Early life=== Simpson spent her early years in Newcastle, where her father F. G. Simpson was Director of Archaeological Field Research and went to school at [[Penrhos College]]. She served as a nurse during the [[Second World War]].<ref name='ARA' />
===Career=== After the war, Simpson studied at [[UCL Institute of Archaeology]], graduating with a Diploma in European Archaeology in 1948. Between 1950 and 1954 she was a research assistant to [[Eric Birley]] at [[Durham University]].<ref name='ARA' /> Between 1950 and 1972 Simpson was the Honorary Curator of the [[John Clayton (town clerk)|Clayton Collection]] of antiquities at [[Cilurnum|Chesters Roman fort]].<ref name='FCM'>{{cite thesis |last=McIntosh |first=Frances C. |date=2017 |title=The Clayton Collection: an archaeological appraisal of a 19th century collection |publisher=Newcastle University |page=3 |url=https://theses.ncl.ac.uk/dspace/bitstream/10443/3687/1/McIntosh%2C%20F%202017.pdf |access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> She undertook postgraduate study at [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]] and was awarded her PhD from Oxford in 1960. The subject of this thesis was published in 1964 as ''Britons and the Roman Army: A Study of Wales and the Southern Pennines in the 1st-3rd Centuries''.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=[[Leslie Alcock|Alcock, L.]] |date=1965 |title=Review.Grace Simpson, Britons and the Roman Army. London: Gregg Press, 1964. Pp. xi + 191, with 3 plates, 24 figs. and one folder. £3. |journal=[[Journal of Roman Studies]] |volume=55 |pages=293-295}}</ref> She taught at Oxford for the Department of Extra-Mural Studies and was a visiting fellow at [[Haverford College]], Pennsylvania.<ref name='ARA' />
Simpson's study of the late [[Joseph Stanfield]]'s investigations into samian ware resulted in the 1958 publication of ''Central Gaulish Potters'', which remains an essential work for the study of the subject more than fifty years on.<ref name='ARA' /> She was one of the early member of the [[Rei cretariae Romanae fautores]], a specialist study group for Roman ceramicists, following its founding 1957 and organised the 14th Congress of the society in Oxford and London in September 1984.<ref>{{cite article |author1=Wells, C. M. |date=2010 |title=FIFTY YEARS OF ROMAN POTTERY STUDIES. RCRF presidential address, Cadiz, September 2008 |journal=REI CRETARIÆ ROMANÆ FAVTORVM ACTA |volume=41 |pages=5-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fautores.org/pages/historia-fautorum.htm |title=HISTORIA FAVTORVM: A (partly personal) illustrated history of the RCRF |author1=Susanne Zabehlicky-Scheffenegger |access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref>
==Select publications== *Simpson, G. 1948. ''Guide to Chesters Museum with notes on the Roman fort, bridge and bath-house etc.'' Durham. *Simpson. G. 1964. ''Britons and the Roman Army: A Studt of Wales and the Southern Provinces in the 1st-3rd Centuries''. London. *Simpson, F. G. (Edited by Simpon, G.). 1976. ''Watermills and Military Works on Hadrian's Wall. Excavations in Northumberland''. Kendal. *Simpson, G. 2000. ''Roman Weapons, Tools, Bronze Equipment and Brooches from Neuss: Nouaesium Excavations 1955-1972'' (BAR International Series 862).
