{{Onesource|date=August 2013}} {{Infobox person |name = Piers Brendon |honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSL|size=100%}} |image = |caption = |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1940|12|21|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Stratton, Cornwall|Stratton]], [[Cornwall]] |nationality = British |occupation = [[Writer]] |education = [[Shrewsbury School]] |alma_mater = [[Magdalene College, Cambridge|Magdalene College]] |years_active = |known_for = |notable_works = }}
'''Piers Brendon''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSL}} (born 21 December 1940) is a British writer, known for historical and biographical works. He was educated at [[Shrewsbury School]] and [[Magdalene College, Cambridge|Magdalene College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], where he read history. He earned a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] degree with his thesis, ''[[Hurrell Froude]] and the [[Oxford Movement]]'', which was published, with much modification, in 1974.
From 1965 to 1978, he was lecturer in history, then principal lecturer and head of department, at what is now [[Anglia Ruskin University]]. From 1979 onwards he has worked as a free-lance writer of books, journalism and for television. From 1995 he has been a fellow of [[Churchill College, Cambridge|Churchill College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]] and was keeper of the [[Churchill Archives Centre]] from 1995 to 2001, taking over from [[Correlli Barnett]]. He was succeeded by Allen Packwood.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/people/view/allen-packwood/ | title=Allen Packwood | publisher=Churchill College | accessdate=February 14, 2017}}</ref>
