==20th century== {| class="wikitable" width="100%"
! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1955 || || The rule of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Anglo]]-[[Khedivate of Egypt|Egyptian]] [[condominium (international law)|condominium]] ended. |- | || ''[[First Sudanese Civil War]]'': The war began. |- | 1956 || 1 January || Sudan achieved independence. |- | 1958 || || General [[Ibrahim Abboud]] staged a military ''coup'' against the elected government. |- | 1962 || || Civil war spread to southern Sudan with the ascendance of the [[Anyanya]] separatist movement. |- | 1964 || Oct || A revolution overthrew [[Ibrahim Abboud|Abboud's]] regime. |- | 1969 || May || [[Gaafar Nimeiry]] led a military ''coup''. |- | 1971 || || ''[[1971 Sudanese coup d'état]]'': The leaders of an attempted [[Sudanese Communist Party|Communist]] ''coup'' against [[Gaafar Nimeiry|Nimeiry]] failed and were executed. |- | 1972 || || The [[Addis Ababa Agreement (1972)]], reached between the Sudanese government and the [[Anyanya]], created a self-governing region in the south of the country. |- | 1978 || || Oil was discovered in [[Bentiu]]. |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1983 || || ''[[Second Sudanese Civil War]]'': A war began between government forces and the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA)]] led by [[John Garang]]. |- | || [[Gaafar Nimeiry|Nimeiry]] introduced ''[[sharia]]''. |- | 1985 || || [[Gaafar Nimeiry|Nimeiry]] was deposed and replaced by the [[Transitional Military Council]]. |- | 1986 || || [[Sadiq al-Mahdi]] became Prime Minister in a coalition government following elections. |- | 1988 || || The [[Democratic Unionist Party (Sudan)]] drafted a cease-fire with the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] which was not implemented. |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1989 || || The government was overthrown in a ''coup''. |- | 30 June || [[Omar al-Bashir]] assumed the office of President. |- | 1993 || 16 October || [[Omar al-Bashir|Bashir]] was appointed President. |- | 1995 || || [[Egypt]]ian President [[Hosni Mubarak]] blames Sudan for an attempted assassination. |- | 1998 || 20 August || The [[Al-Shifa pharmaceutical factory]] was destroyed by [[United States]] cruise missiles. |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1999 || || A state of emergency was declared by President [[Omar al-Bashir|Bashir]] following a power struggle with [[Hassan al-Turabi]]. |- | || Oil exports from Sudan began. |- | rowspan="3" valign="top" | 2000 || September || The Governor of [[Khartoum]] banned women from working in public places. |- | September || President [[Omar al-Bashir|Bashir]] met the leaders of the [[National Democratic Alliance (Sudan)]] for the first time. |- | December || [[Omar al-Bashir|Bashir]] was re-elected for a five-year term as President. |}
==21st century== {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | rowspan="8" valign="top" | 2001 || February || [[Hassan al-Turabi|Al-Turabi]] was arrested for signing a memorandum with the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]]. |- | March || The [[United Nations|United Nations (UN)]] [[World Food Programme]] struggled to feed millions facing starvation. |- | April || The [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] threatened to attack foreign oil workers. |- | June || Peace talks in [[Nairobi]] broke down. |- | July || [[Egypt]] and [[Libya]] proposed a peace plan for Sudan. |- | September || The [[United Nations|UN]] lifted sanctions against Sudan. |- | October || [[United States]] [[United States Senator|Senator]] [[John Danforth]] was appointed Special Envoy to Sudan. |- | November || The [[United States]] imposed sanctions on Sudan. |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 2002 || January || A ceasefire was agreed between the government and the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]]. |- | 20 July || ''Second Sudanese Civil War'': The [[Machakos Protocol]] ended the nineteen-year civil war. |- | 2003 || February || ''[[War in Darfur]]'': The war began. |- | rowspan="3" valign="top" | 2004 || January || The army moved into [[Darfur]] to quell the rebellion, prompting hundreds of thousands of refugees to flee into neighbouring [[Chad]]. |- | March || A [[United Nations|UN]] official accused pro-government ''[[Janjaweed]]'' militias of carrying out systematic killings in [[Darfur]]. |- | September || [[United States]] [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[Colin Powell]] described the [[Darfur]] killings as genocide. |- | rowspan="7" valign="top" | 2005 || 9 January || The [[Comprehensive Peace Agreement]] was signed between the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] and the government. |- | March || The [[United Nations]] [[United Nations Security Council|Security Council]] authorised sanctions against any violators of the [[Darfur]] ceasefire. |- | June || [[Hassan al-Turabi|Al-Turabi]] was freed. |- | July || [[John Garang]] was sworn in as vice-president. |- | 1 August || [[John Garang|Garang]] died in a plane crash and was succeeded by [[Salva Kiir Mayardit]]. |- | September || A power-sharing government was established. |- | October || An autonomous government was formed in southern Sudan. |- | rowspan="3" valign="top" | 2006 || May || The government signed a peace accord with a [[Darfur]] rebel group, the [[Sudan Liberation Movement]]. |- | October || [[Jan Pronk]], head of the [[United Nations Mission in Sudan]], was expelled from the country. |- | November || [[African Union]] peacekeepers extended their stay in [[Darfur]] for a further six months. |- | rowspan="5" valign="top" | 2007 || May || The [[United States]] placed fresh sanctions on Sudan. |- | 31 July || [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1769]] authorised twenty-six thousand peacekeepers for [[Darfur]]. |- | August || ''[[2007 Sudan floods]]'': Floods began. |- | September || ''2007 Sudan floods'': The floods ended. |- | November || ''[[Sudanese teddy bear blasphemy case]]'': A [[United Kingdom|British]] teacher was imprisoned for naming a teddy bear Muhammad. |}
